The sensitivity of the carbon dots toward Cu2+ was investigated by measuring fluorescence emission from the carbon dot solution in the presence of different concentrations of Cu2+. As expected, the fluorescence intensity was gradually quenched as the Cu2+ concentration increased (Fig. 5c). The Stern-Volmer plot was obtained and showed a linear regime in the concentration range from 1 to 5 μM (Fig. 5d) [27]. The detection limit, determined from the 3σ/slope where σ is the standard deviation from the blank sample, was 0.16 μM, comparable to previous studies on unmodified carbon dots (Table 1
                           ). Based on the Stern-Volmer plot, the fluorescence emission intensity became saturated when the concentration of added Cu2+ reached approximately 100 μM, suggesting the maximum Cu2+ adsorption on the carbon dot surface had been reached. Based on the calculation method derived in our previous report [48], this is equivalent to a surface coverage of 30 ions/particle or 0.5 ions/nm2 and an adsorption capacity of 31 mg g−1, which is comparable to previous reports in the literature (detailed calculation is provided in the supplementary information) (Table 2
                           ). This value is relatively high for unmodified adsorbent materials. The sensing selectivity and high adsorption capacity would allow our unmodified, ready-to-use carbon dots to act simultaneously as sensor and adsorbent of Cu2+. The sensitivity and adsorption capacity can be further improved simply by surface passivation. This, however, is beyond the scope of this work, as the goal was to demonstrate that our unmodified, label-free carbon dots exhibit satisfactory selectivity and sensitivity toward Cu2+.

The practical use of our carbon dots for the detection of Cu2+ions in tap, river, and drinking water was evaluated using DI water as standard sample. As real samples may not contain Cu2+ ions, we spiked the water samples with standard Cu2+ solution. As shown in Table 3
                           , the percentage recoveries were in the acceptable range of 98% to 111% and the relative standard deviation in percentage (%RSD) values were between 0.17% and 0.42%. This indicates that our carbon dots effectively sensed Cu2+ in real water samples with high accuracy. We further used the carbon dot-coated paper sensors to test the selectivity of the carbon dots toward Cu2+ in real water samples. These results show that the relative RGB values were consistent with the percentage recovery of spiked Cu2+ ions, because both percentage recovery and RGB values corresponded to the Cu2+ spiking concentrations (Fig. 7
                           ). This confirms the consistency of our carbon dots as Cu2+ sensors in both solution and solid phase. This confirmed the practicality of the carbon dots and paper-based sensors developed in this work as accurate, reliable fluorescent probes for determining Cu2+ levels in real samples.
